  "twitter_thread": {
    "tweet1": "Think your credit card interest is 42%? Think again. With the 18% GST trap, you are actually paying closer to 51% per year. That 3.5% monthly quote is designed to hide the real cost of your debt.",
    "tweet2": "Banks won't tell you that GST is charged on interest, not just fees. For every ₹10,000 in interest you owe, the government takes an extra ₹1,800. This tax compounding makes escaping debt almost impossible.",
    "tweet3": "The honest verdict: Credit cards are the most expensive way to borrow in India. The 'Minimum Amount Due' is a trap designed to keep you paying 51% interest while your balance barely moves.",
    "tweet4": "Stop falling for the monthly percentage trap. Learn how the math really works and how to break free from the 51% cycle here: https://lastemi.com/blog/credit-card-gst-interest-hidden-cost"
  },
  "linkedin_post": "The hidden 51% interest rate on your credit card. Most Indian banks advertise credit card interest rates at 3.5% per month. On the surface, this looks like 42% per annum. However, this figure is intentionally misleading. When you factor in the 18% GST on interest charges and the effect of monthly compounding, your effective annual percentage rate (APR) spikes to approximately 51%. This means if you carry a balance that generates ₹5,000 in monthly interest, you are paying an additional ₹900 in tax every single month. Banks rarely highlight this because their business model relies on you staying in high-interest debt. The Minimum Amount Due is not a helpful suggestion; it is a calculated tool to ensure you continue paying these predatory rates for years. At LastEMI, we believe in radical transparency. Understanding that you are paying over half your principal in interest and taxes every year
